00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:19.360
But if your school was anything
like mine, then once

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:22.510
a year, the thing got hauled
out, switched on, and

00:01:22.510 --> 00:01:26.010
absolutely nothing happened.

00:01:26.010 --> 00:01:29.750
Now, what's supposed to happen
is that the belt peels

00:01:29.750 --> 00:01:34.360
electrons off the rollers, and
it builds up a positive static

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:36.970
charge on the top of the dome.

00:01:36.970 --> 00:01:39.000
I've got a bunch of electrodes
which are hooked up

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:40.350
to the Van de Graff.

00:01:40.350 --> 00:01:44.360
And when I switch it on, every
other electrode will become

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:46.110
positively charged.

00:01:46.110 --> 00:01:50.140
And the rest of them will stay
at ground, or zero volts.

00:01:50.140 --> 00:01:53.990
And my particle today is a
ping pong ball which I've

00:01:53.990 --> 00:01:57.780
covered with a metallic paint
so it can hold a charge.

00:01:57.780 --> 00:02:00.960
And when that sits on one of
the positive electrodes, it

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:03.640
becomes positively
charged itself.

00:02:03.640 --> 00:02:05.930
And you should have learned,
around about the Van de Graaff

00:02:05.930 --> 00:02:09.419
lesson in school, that
like charges repel.

00:02:09.419 --> 00:02:13.470
So it actually pushes away from
the positive electrode.

00:02:13.470 --> 00:02:17.020
And then, when it sits on the
ground electrode, it loses all

00:02:17.020 --> 00:02:19.620
of that charge and becomes
neutral again.

00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:23.410
But it keeps rolling across to
the next positive electrode,

00:02:23.410 --> 00:02:25.640
and the cycle repeats again.

00:02:25.640 --> 00:02:27.830
And each time this happens,
it gains a

00:02:27.830 --> 00:02:29.400
little bit of momentum.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:32.526
So it gets faster and faster
and faster, if the Van de

00:02:32.526 --> 00:02:33.200
Graaff works.

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:36.450
So, if you'll all do me a favour
and just kind of will

00:02:36.450 --> 00:02:39.815
it on with all of your will
power, I'll just switch it on.

00:02:48.810 --> 00:02:49.440
It's all right.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:51.600
You can breathe again now.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:02.600
Now, it turns out, you can't
roll protons around in a salad

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:04.290
bowl, unfortunately.

00:03:04.290 --> 00:03:07.270
You need to actually put them
in an ultra-high vacuum and

00:03:07.270 --> 00:03:09.350
then use magnetic fields
to actually bend

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:11.280
them around in a circle.

00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:17.535
Now, it also turns out that
a real proton is about 200

00:03:17.535 --> 00:03:21.115
trillion times smaller than
a ping pong ball.

00:03:21.115 --> 00:03:23.490
And it can't change
its charge.

00:03:23.490 --> 00:03:26.190
So we've made a bit of a cheat
here, because we've kept the

00:03:26.190 --> 00:03:28.190
electric field constant.

00:03:28.190 --> 00:03:31.020
In a real accelerator, you have
to change the electric

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:34.670
field to keep accelerating
the particle around.

00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:37.480
And you have to do it
pretty quickly.

00:03:37.480 --> 00:03:40.830
Because the protons in the Large
Hadron Collider, well,

00:03:40.830 --> 00:03:44.320
they're traveling at just
a tiny fraction below

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:45.630
the speed of light.

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:53.780
And the speed of light is
299,792,458 meters a second.

00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:56.960
So, keeping that in time with
increasing speed of the

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:59.900
particles is pretty tricky.

00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:02.750
And we're not just talking
about one particle.

00:04:02.750 --> 00:04:05.640
We actually accelerate billions
or even trillions of

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:07.850
them all at the same time.

00:04:07.850 --> 00:04:10.430
And they all have the same
electric charge, so they all

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:12.460
try and repel against
each other.

00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:16.690
And trust me, that causes all
sorts of other problems.

00:04:16.690 --> 00:04:20.869
So, as models go, this one is
a little bit simplified.

00:04:20.869 --> 00:04:23.950
But there's two things about
real accelerators that this

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:26.440
can actually show us.

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:30.250
The first one is looking at
the shape of the bowl, the

00:04:30.250 --> 00:04:33.430
